Observation from bivariate analysis :¶

1. Substances such as superplastic , slag and cement (on it own) positively strengthen the concrete regardless of¶
aging.¶
2. Regardless of aging of the concrete, lower the water to cement ratio , stronger the concrete is with the¶
exception of aging for almost a year (270 - 400) where the strength remains constant.¶
3. In case of Ash and FIne aggregates , there is on an average a slightly postive linear relationship with the concrete strength in general.¶
However aging seems to play an important role here, For example aging the cement till 2 quarters clearly yields higher strength than¶
aging cement with in one quarter of the year.¶
4. Keeping the aging of cement within 2 quarters , lower quantity of coarse aggregetes between 800-900 kg/m3 yields better concrete¶
strength whereas aging the cement more than 2 quarters ( 6 months) requires higher quantity of coarse aggregetes to improve the¶
concrete strength.¶

3. Feature Engineering¶

Feature Extraction:¶

From the univariate and bivariate analysis, Following can be done:¶

- Looking the impact of aging more precisely when binned needs to be convered to a categorical variable with labels in quarters.¶

- The skewness of graphs for Slag , Ash and Super plastic concentrations can be removed by replacing zero values with mena/median for better predictions.¶

- Instead of treating cement and water as seperate parmaters , water cement ratio can be used in the analysis ( the W/C ratio is already added as part of the Bivariate anlysis)¶

Data Modeling¶

Since the target variable is continous we can try simple logistic regression first and then increase the complexity of the model by going for polynomial logistic regression of n degree( n = 2 or more)¶

K-fold cross validation method will be used to determine and compare the complexities of these models¶

print(results)
lm_k_fold_R2 = results.mean()*100.0
print("The average R2 through K-Fold validation for linear model: %.3f%% (%.3f%%)" % (results.mean()*100.0, results.std()*100.0))

params = {'n_estimators': 600, 'max_depth': 4, 'min_samples_split': 2,
          'learning_rate': 0.01, 'loss': 'ls'}

score = boost_model.score(X_test,y_test)
# Explained variance score: 1 is perfect prediction

y_predict = boost_model.predict(X_test)

Conclusion :¶

- From the above table , it is clear that Models such as random forest and gradient boosters perform way better than complex polynomial model of higher degrees , both in terms of R2 and MSE¶

- Random Forest has slightly higher R2 whereas Gradient boosting has slightly lower MSE . In such a scenario where average R2 after validation slightly differ, the decision should be base on minimizing the Mean Squared Errors.¶

- Therefore Gradient boosting works as the best model in determining the Concrete strength from the given content amounts.¶
